        <head xml:id="pl-l4d3c2-Hd1e109">CAP. II</head>
        <head xml:id="pl-l4d3c2-Hd1e112" type="question-title">On the form of baptism</head>
        <p xml:id="pl-l4d3c2-d1e115">
          But what is the word, which when added to the element, 
          it becomes a sacrament?
        </p>
        <p xml:id="pl-l4d3c2-d1e118">
          The truth teaches you, 
          which treating the form of its sacrament, 
          says to his disciples:
          <cit>
            <quote xml:id="pl-l4d3c2-Qd1e122" source="http://scta.info/resource/mt28_19">
              Go, teach all nations, 
              baptizing them in the name of the Father and thed Son and the Holy Spirit
            </quote>
            <bibl>Matthaeus 28:19</bibl>
          </cit>. 
          Therefore the invocation of the Trinity 
          is the called the word by which baptism is consecrated; 
          and this i the form of the words, 
          under which baptism is treated.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="pl-l4d3c2-d1e121">
          Whence  
          <ref xml:id="pl-l4d3c2-Rd1e134" corresp="#pl-l4d3c2-Qd1e123"><name>Pope Zacharias</name></ref>: 
          <cit>
            <quote xml:id="pl-l4d3c2-Qd1e123" source="http://scta.info/resource/gd-p3d4-d1e1331">
              It was firmly decreed in the Synod of England, 
              whoever was dipped without the invocation of the Trinity, 
              that there is no sacrament of regeneration; 
              which is entirely true, 
              because someone were dipped in the font of baptism 
              without the invocation of the Trinity, 
              they would not be a perfected Christian, 
              unless they were baptized in the name of the Father and the Son 
              and the Holy Spirit.
             </quote>
            <bibl>Gratianus, De Consecratione, d. 4 (t. 1, 1389)</bibl>
          </cit>.
        </p>
      </div>
